name: AJEnglish
text:
THREAD

For months, Mali has been mired in a political crisis marked by large anti-gov't rallies & failed mediation attempts by regional leaders.

Here's a timeline of the crisis that led to President Keita's resignation following a military coup üëá https://t.co/QJCwynRLv8 https://t.co/xxB7ImcJbR

name: AJEnglish
text: In March, the first round of Mali's long-delayed parliamentary election proceeded despite the abduction of opposition leader Soumaila Cisse by unidentified gunmen, the growing threat of COVID-19 and the possibility of attacks by armed groups https://t.co/KTg7CgBMlw https://t.co/5ZcH5zI9qO

name: AJEnglish
text: On April 19, round two of the parliamentary vote was disrupted by incidents that prevented some voters from casting their ballots. On April 30, the Constitutional Court overturned results for 31 seats, giving Keita's party the majority & sparking protests https://t.co/KTg7CgBMlw https://t.co/nYHpivCOzA

name: AJEnglish
text:
On May 30, Mali's main opposition parties and civil society groups form a new opposition alliance, calling for protests to demand President Keita's resignation. 

In June, thousands joined anti-gov't protests in the streets of Bamako https://t.co/KTg7CgBMlw https://t.co/jwhasi6tXB

name: AJEnglish
text:
In early July, at least 14 people were killed in clashes between security forces and protesters after mass demonstrations turned violent. 

It was the worst political strife Mali had seen in years https://t.co/KTg7CgBMlw https://t.co/OV9Cuwj3v3

name: AJEnglish
text: On July 18, the opposition alliance rejected a plan proposed by international mediators to defuse tensions, insisting that President Keita step down https://t.co/KTg7CgBMlw https://t.co/R3EKRa294T

name: AJEnglish
text: Just after midnight, on August 19, President Keita announced his resignation and dissolved his gov't just hours after mutinying soldiers detained him at gunpoint, plunging the country into political uncertainty https://t.co/KTg7CgBMlw https://t.co/fx4QO4OyKx
